explanation:
For MISRA dead-code analysis we must know which branches and statements in queue_auth_required_response3_inner can actually execute. The symbols below either control compilation/time-of-execution branching, determine run-time branch outcomes, or affect side-effect/early-return behavior and so are required to decide whether any operation is dead (removable without effect).

- MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_ALGO3_NON_SESSION: used in the initial bitmask test; required to know whether that if-condition can be true at runtime.
- MHD_DIGEST_BASE_ALGO_MD5, MHD_DIGEST_BASE_ALGO_SHA256, MHD_DIGEST_BASE_ALGO_SHA512_256: bitmask constants used to select s_algo; needed to determine reachability of the algorithm-selection branches.
- MHD_MD5_SUPPORT, MHD_SHA256_SUPPORT, MHD_SHA512_256_SUPPORT: build-time macros that enable/disable blocks of code; required because disabled blocks are not present (affects dead-code determination).
- MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_ALGO3_MD5, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_ALGO3_SHA256, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_ALGO3_SHA512_256: enum values assigned to s_algo and used in later comparisons; affect which algorithm-specific copy/size code executes.
- MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_QOP_AUTH_INT, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_QOP_AUTH_INT, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_QOP_NONE: constants used in mqop masking and comparisons; required to know which qop-related branches execute.
- digest_init_one_time and get_base_digest_algo: digest_init_one_time return value causes a panic (early termination) on failure; get_base_digest_algo result influences digest_init_one_time call – both are needed to see if code after them can be reached.
- MHD_get_master and (type and field) master->nonce_nc_size: MHD_get_master() is called and its returned object's nonce_nc_size is checked for zero which causes an early return; the master type and its nonce_nc_size field are required to know whether that check can be false/true.
- calculate_add_nonce_with_retry: return value affects logging and later behavior; needed to decide whether following code (and side-effects) always/ever execute.
- digest_ext_error and MHD_DIGEST_HAS_EXT_ERROR: used in an #ifdef-guarded path after calculate_add_nonce_with_retry failure; required to determine whether that failure path contains additional behavior (affecting dead-code determination).
- digest_get_size and NONCE_STD_LEN: used to compute sizes and assertions around the nonce write; their values/sizes determine whether related buffer-copy/nonce-writing code is reachable and valid.
- MHD_str_quote: used to quote realm/opaque/domain and can cause an early return (too large); required to know whether quoting calls can lead to returns and thus make subsequent code unreachable.
- MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_, _MHD_AUTH_DIGEST_BASE, _MHD_AUTH_DIGEST_MAX_PARAM_SIZE: macros/constants used in size calculations and limits, which influence whether checks trigger early returns (dead vs live code).
- MHD_TOKEN_AUTH_, _MHD_MD5_TOKEN, _MHD_SHA256_TOKEN, _MHD_SHA512_256_TOKEN: string tokens copied into the buffer depending on branches; needed to know which memcpy branches are live.
- MHD_HTTP_HEADER_WWW_AUTHENTICATE, MHD_HEADER_KIND, MHD_add_response_entry_no_alloc_: the header name/allocation and the call to add the response entry determine the success/failure branch toward MHD_queue_response or the fallback that frees hdr_name. These symbols are required to know if that success path executes (so code freeing hdr_name is not dead).
- MHD_queue_response: called on the successful add-path and returns from the function; its behavior affects reachability of code after the call and whether earlier operations (setting *buf_ptr = NULL) are effective.
- MHD_PANIC, MHD_DLOG, HAVE_MESSAGES: logging and panic macros affect whether code paths lead to program termination or only log; MHD_PANIC causes program termination/unreachable continuation — important to decide whether code following a panic is dead/unreachable.
- mhd_assert: assertions may abort in some builds; required to understand whether subsequent code is guaranteed to execute.
- malloc, free, memcpy, strlen, memchr: standard-library calls whose failure/results cause early returns or control flow (malloc NULL return causes function to return); required to reason about whether later code is reachable.
- MHD_NO and MHD_HTTP_UNAUTHORIZED: return/value constants used in returns; needed to decide which return paths are actual exits.

In short: include all compile-time flags, the bitmask constants and enum values used in the conditional logic, the helper functions that can return early (digest_init_one_time, MHD_get_master->nonce_nc_size check, MHD_str_quote, calculate_add_nonce_with_retry, MHD_add_response_entry_no_alloc_, malloc), and the logging/panic/assert macros that alter control flow. With these symbols the next analyzer can decide which branches are genuinely unreachable or merely conditional and therefore whether any statement in this function is dead code.
